16:44.368 --> 16:46.451
On the seventh day, you're going to march around seven times.

16:46.831 --> 16:49.635
And then at the end of the seventh lap, you're going to take these ramsorns.

16:49.655 --> 16:50.536
You're going to blow them.

16:50.556 --> 16:52.619
And then everybody's going to scream at the top of their lungs.

16:52.699 --> 16:53.000
I don't know.

16:53.080 --> 16:54.802
Maybe that's not that much, but it's something.

16:55.778 --> 16:58.084
And so they do it, and watch what happens on the seventh day.

16:58.666 --> 17:01.614
When the people heard the sound of the rans horn, they shouted as loud as they could.

17:02.536 --> 17:03.058
Oh, I don't know.

17:03.078 --> 17:04.461
That sounded like something like that.

17:05.885 --> 17:07.309
Suddenly the walls collapsed.

17:08.171 --> 17:12.082
And the Israelites, this is the part we don't focus on.

17:12.258 --> 17:14.020
We focus on the part that the walls came down.

17:14.060 --> 17:16.403
Oh my gosh, the river, the Red Sea parted.

17:16.703 --> 17:17.645
Okay, that's awesome.

17:17.885 --> 17:19.026
Here's the part we don't focus on.

17:19.267 --> 17:24.113
And then the Israelites charged straight into the town without any battle experience.

17:24.453 --> 17:27.096
They don't even have a sword, they have no armor, and what did they do?

17:27.156 --> 17:28.959
They captured the town.

17:30.140 --> 17:31.282
That's the part we tend to leave out.

17:32.243 --> 17:33.624
Who captured the town?

17:35.106 --> 17:36.208
Did God capture the town?

17:36.548 --> 17:37.649
No, no, no, no.

17:37.669 --> 17:38.591
God removed the barrier.

17:40.152 --> 17:41.394
He says, you Joshua.

17:41.826 --> 17:46.992
You lead these people into the town and you capture the town.

17:47.032 --> 17:52.978
I'm telling you, every upgrade always involves a combination of your effort and God's effort.

17:53.299 --> 17:56.222
A couple years ago, I came across a book called Lead the Field by Earl Nightingale.

17:56.262 --> 17:57.543
It's a great story in here.

17:57.563 --> 17:58.424
I think it's pretty funny.

17:59.666 --> 18:02.268
There's a story about a preacher who was driving by a beautiful farm.

18:02.288 --> 18:07.314
The fields were beautifully cultivated and abundant with well-cared for crops.

18:07.778 --> 18:11.704
The fences, house, and the barn were clean, neat, and freshly painted.

18:12.726 --> 18:18.895
A row of fine trees led from the road to the house where there was a shaded lawn and many flower beds.

18:19.356 --> 18:21.078
It was a beautiful sight to behold.

18:21.819 --> 18:31.294
When the farmer who was working in the field got to the end of a row near the road, the preacher stopped his car, opened the door, and yelled, God has blessed you with a beautiful farm.

18:32.396 --> 18:34.098
The farmer stopped and thought for a moment.

18:34.839 --> 18:36.562
They then replied, yes, he has.

18:36.930 --> 18:41.615
And I'm grateful, but you should have seen this place when he had it all to himself.

18:44.799 --> 18:55.670
The farmer understood that he had been blessed with a fine farm, but he was also aware that it was his own love and own labor that had brought it to its present state.

18:57.132 --> 18:57.552
Do you see it?

18:58.093 --> 18:58.534
Yes or no?

18:59.154 --> 18:59.615
Do you see it?

19:00.255 --> 19:05.201
There's a combination of our effort and God's effort.

19:05.221 --> 19:06.322
You say, well, how much?

19:06.754 --> 19:07.295
I don't know.

19:08.497 --> 19:11.422
40, 60, 50, 50, 35, 65.

19:11.522 --> 19:14.147
I don't know what the percentages are.

19:14.568 --> 19:20.258
By the way, when God knocked the walls down around Jericho, he never did that again.

19:20.278 --> 19:22.642
It was the only time.

19:25.058 --> 19:26.320
The percentages change.

19:26.620 --> 19:27.321
You say, how much?

19:27.681 --> 19:29.063
How much should I push?

19:29.103 --> 19:41.277
How much is my responsibility when it comes to upgrading my health and fitness or upgrading my finances or upgrading my marriage or upgrading my relationship with my parents or upgrading my grades or whatever, whatever you're trying to upgrade?

19:41.297 --> 19:43.300
How much is my responsibility?

19:43.680 --> 19:44.441
I don't know.

19:44.681 --> 19:45.663
So here's my answer.

19:47.044 --> 19:48.466
As much as you possibly can.

19:49.922 --> 19:54.249
as much as you pass, because you don't know when the Jordan River is gonna part.

19:54.389 --> 19:56.913
You don't know when the walls of Jericho are gonna come down.

19:57.233 --> 19:58.335
You have no idea.

19:58.575 --> 20:01.439
So you can't just count on God showing up.

20:02.581 --> 20:04.744
You have to do what only you can do.

20:04.764 --> 20:05.926
You gotta do your part.

20:05.946 --> 20:07.869
You gotta show up and put your feet in the water.

20:07.989 --> 20:09.852
You gotta march around the city once a day.

20:09.992 --> 20:11.495
You gotta blow the ram sword.

20:11.715 --> 20:19.026
What are the things that God is saying to you that you have to do if you wanna experience an upgrade in that relationship or in your finances?

20:20.866 --> 20:23.989
I've been studying a guy named Anders Ericsson for several years.

20:24.910 --> 20:29.054
He's a Swedish psychologist and professor of psychology at Florida State University.

20:29.755 --> 20:36.742
He's got a mountain of research, and he is now recognized as an international authority on the area of expertise.

20:38.444 --> 20:46.352
People have become, who have reached the top 1% in their field, specifically in chess, in medicine, in music, and in sports.

20:46.992 --> 20:48.594
Those are the key areas that he studies.

20:49.858 --> 20:52.542
He's an expert, he's an expert at expertise.

20:54.105 --> 20:59.453
His latest book is called Peak, P-E-A-K, the study of performance, fascinating research.

20:59.473 --> 21:04.180
His body of research has basically come down to this, I'll try to narrow it down into one big idea.

21:05.182 --> 21:15.538
He says that when a person, whether it's with an instrument or whether it's with a hockey puck or a violin or chess or whatever it is, if a person will practice

21:16.226 --> 21:26.643
For about 10,000 hours, sometimes 15, sometimes 20,000 in their life, hours, they can reach the top 1% in their field.

21:26.964 --> 21:36.400
But not just any type of practice, not just comfortable practice, like going out and swinging a bat or shooting some free throws or playing a couple of songs that you're familiar with, that you've done before.

21:36.460 --> 21:37.782
No, no, no, not that type of practice.

21:38.563 --> 21:42.610
The practice where you're trying to play something that you can just barely play.

21:43.170 --> 21:46.354
when you're trying to make a move that you can just barely do.

21:47.054 --> 21:54.102
When you're trying to hit a pitch that you could just barely hit right on the edge of failure, right in your discomfort zone.

21:54.402 --> 21:58.727
The people who reach the top 1% are the people who practice what he calls it.

21:58.747 --> 22:06.275
Deliberate practice, focus practice, stretching beyond what you're capable of doing right on the edge of failure where we don't want to be.

22:07.757 --> 22:08.658
See, did you catch that?

22:08.994 --> 22:11.938
We don't like being there because we feel like I'm not very good.

22:12.278 --> 22:12.959
I'm failing.

22:13.340 --> 22:14.121
I'm missing.

22:14.441 --> 22:15.723
I don't know how to make this move.

22:15.983 --> 22:17.225
I don't know how to play this song.

22:18.006 --> 22:20.730
And most people just back away and they go back to what they're familiar with.

22:21.651 --> 22:22.212
I'm good here.

22:23.073 --> 22:27.979
Well, the best of the best of the best push and stretch and they push and they stretch.

22:28.700 --> 22:30.643
And that's exactly what Albert Einstein said.

22:32.225 --> 22:38.994
One must develop an instinct for what one can just barely achieve with one's greatest efforts.

22:39.138 --> 22:40.220
This is David Goggins.

22:42.203 --> 22:54.141
I'm just barely surviving here, but I'm pushing past this discomfort zone, this 40% rule, and I'm going into that space, that 60%, and those are the people that stretch and get better and better and better.

22:54.421 --> 22:55.963
How much should you and I push?

22:57.786 --> 23:02.694
Man, there's a lot of room there as much as you possibly can.

